p: Phytochemical C6, tectol, has binding energy of −8.1 kcal/mol. C6 is a naphthoquinone derivative [ 53] present in Tectona grandis and Tecomella undulata. Tectona grandis has been reported to have anti-inflammatory and antiparasitic activities [ 45]. Tecomella undulata has been used to treat syphilis and also reported to have anti-inflammatory and anti-HIV activities [ 54]. Additionally, Tectol has been reported to inhibit farnesyltransferase enzyme [ 55]. Figure 7f shows the cathepsin L residues that form hydrogen bonds or π-π stacking interactions with C6. The pyran group of C6 is involved in a C-H⋯O type hydrogen bond with residue L144. The catalytic residue C25 forms a C-H⋯S type hydrogen bond with C6. The other catalytic residue H163 forms a N-H⋯O type hydrogen bond with C6. Also, the residue W189 forms both face-to-face and face-to-edge type of π-π stacking interaction with C6. Further, C6 forms hydrophobic contacts with G23, L144 and W189.
